04636nam a22006735i 9780231552295DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020049323  a97802315522957 a10.7312/nama197682doi  a(DE-B1597)590379  a(OCoLC)1266227821  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aDS485.P66bN36 2021 4aDS485.P66bN36 2021eb 7aHIS0170002bisacsh04a954.02/92231 aNamakkal, Jessica, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnsettling Utopia :bThe Making and Unmaking of French India /cJessica Namakkal. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Studies in International and Global History00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tChronology -- tIntroduction. On Minor Borders and Colonial Time -- tPART I. Making -- t1 Carceral Borders: Exile, Surveillance, and Subversion -- t2 The Future of French India: Decolonization and Settlement at the Borders -- t3 Making the Postcolonial Subject: Goondas, Refugees, and Citizens -- tPART II. Unmaking -- t4 Decolonial Crossings: Settlers, Migrants, Tourists -- t5 From the Ashram to Auroville: Utopia as Settlement -- tConclusion. The Messiness of Colonialism -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tCOLUMBIA STUDIES IN INTERNATIONAL AND GLOBAL HISTORY0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfter India achieved independence from the British in 1947, there remained five scattered territories governed by the French imperial state. It was not until 1962 that France fully relinquished control. Once decolonization took hold across the subcontinent, Western-led ashrams and utopian communities remained in and around the former French territory of Pondicherry—most notably the Sri Aurobindo Ashram and the Auroville experimental township, which continue to thrive and draw tourists today.Unsettling Utopia presents a new account of the history of twentieth-century French India to show how colonial projects persisted beyond formal decolonization. Through the experience of the French territories, Jessica Namakkal recasts the relationships among colonization, settlement, postcolonial sovereignty, utopianism, and liberation, considering questions of borders, exile, violence, and citizenship from the margins. She demonstrates how state-sponsored decolonization—the bureaucratic process of transferring governance from an imperial state to a postcolonial state—rarely aligned with local desires. Namakkal examines the colonial histories of the Aurobindo Ashram and Auroville, arguing that their continued success shows how decolonization paradoxically opened new spaces of settlement, perpetuating imperial power. Challenging conventional markers of the boundaries of the colonial era as well as nationalist narratives, Unsettling Utopia sheds new light on the legacies of colonialism and offers bold thinking on what decolonization might yet mean.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aDecolonizationzIndiaxHistory. 0aUtopiaszIndiaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073907740uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/nama1976840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231552295423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231552295/original  a978-3-11-073907-7  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK